VIRAL MENINGITIS - FRANCE
*************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Sponsored in part by Elsevier, publisher of
The Clinical Journal of Virology
<http://intl.elsevierhealth.com/journals/jocv>
Date: Fri 9 Sep 2005
From: ProMED-mail <prommed@promedmail.org>
Source: Eurosurveillance Weekly 2005 ; 10(9), Thu 8 Sep [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/index-02.asp>

Since the end of May 2005, an increase in the number of viral meningitis
cases has been observed, unevenly distributed throughout mainland France,
with the following regions affected the most: Provence-Alpes-Cote d'Azur
(south east France), Ile de France (Paris and surrounding area),
Rhone-Alpes (south east France), Midi-Pyrenees (south west France), et
Haute-Normandie (north west France) (1).
Information has been collected from virology laboratories participating in
the enterovirus surveillance network and, although biased, they do not
indicate an epidemic on the scale of the 2000 outbreak [illustrated by a
figure in the original text]. However, the increase in case numbers is
greater than that seen in 2001-2004.
Numbers peaked in week 27, and a decrease has been seen since then. [The
enteroviruses] identified were mainly echovirus 30, coxsackievirus group B
type 5, and to a lesser extent, echoviruses 13 and 6. At the beginning of
May (week 18), 11 per cent of samples tested by ligase chain reaction (LCR)
were positive for enterovirus, and this reached 60 per cent in week 29
(18-24 July).
The activity registered by the virology laboratories reflects only a small
part of the admissions to hospital emergency departments for viral
meningitis, as not all patients are sampled for enterovirus testing. In
Ile-de-France, admissions are monitored in 23 emergency departments. Weekly
admissions from 1 May to 24 Jul 2005 (weekly 18 to 29) for viral
meningitis: cases increased until week 26, then decreased [illustrated by a
figure in the original text].
A paper on the past 5 years of enterovirus surveillance in France will be
published in the Bulletin Epidemiologique Hebdomadaire in October 2005, and
a detailed report of the year 2005 is planned for publication in 2006
(<http://www.invs.sante.fr/beh/default.htm>).
Increases in incidence of echoviruses 13 and 30 in Europe were last
mentioned in Eurosurveillance in 2002 [2].
References
----------
1. Institut de veille sanitaire. Epidemie de meningites virales en France.
Le point au 1er aout 2005. 1 Aug 2005.
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2005/le_point_sur/meningites_010805/index.html>
2. Noah N, Reid F. Recent increases in incidence of echoviruses 13 and 30
around Europe. Eurosurveillance Weekly 2002; 6(7): 14/02/2002.
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2002/020214.asp#4>
[byline: Denise Antona1 (<d.antona@invs.sante.fr>) and Jean-Jacques
Chomel2, with the Enterovirus Surveillance Laboratory Network
1 Institut de veille sanitaire, Saint-Maurice, France,
2 Centre national de reference des Enterovirus, Lyon, France]
