ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Viral meningitis in childhood can be associated with infection by certain
enteroviruses or with mumps virus, whereas in adulthood other viruses such
as herpes simplex type 2 may be involved. Headache, neck rigidity, fever
and occasionally vomiting are indicative of viral meningitis. Illness
usually resolves quickly without serious consequence. Viral meningitis is
sometimes described as aseptic or lymphocytic meningitis due to the
predominance of lymphocytes in the cerebrospinal fluid. The members of the
genus _Enterovirus_ (family _Picornaviridae_) associated with meningitis
include various echoviruses, the polioviruses, and A and B type
coxsackieviruses. The predominance of echovirus 30 and coxsackievirus B 5
in France in the current season may reflect the relative prevalence of
these enteroviruses in Northern Europe at the present time. - Mod.CP]
